Use @MockBean instead of @Mock. It tells Spring Boot that you&#39;re mocking an autowired bean.

    @MockBean
    private ModuleRepository repository;

Your test will also have to be annotated with @SpringBootTest

https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/current/reference/html/features.html#features.testing.spring-boot-applications.mocking-beans

If `ModuleRepository` is from a library you don&#39;t control, then define a Spring Bean for it as follows:
```java
@Configuration
public class RepoConfig {
    @Bean
    public ModuleRepository getModuleRepository() {
        return new ModuleRepository();
    }
}
```

Now you can inject it as a Spring Bean using `@Autowired`, or better yet, using construction injection.

After you do this, you can use `@MockBean` in your test:
```java
@MockBean
private ModuleRepository repository;
```

You should initialize all of your non-bean mock objects during the test setup

```
  @Before
  public void setUp() {
    MockitoAnnotations.initMocks(this);
  }

